@NODE "MAIN" "RecoverDelDirPrefs.guide"


          @{fg shine}____________________________________________________________@{fg text}
         @{fg shine}|@{fg text}                                                            |
         @{fg shine}|@{fg text}   @{b}RecoverDelDirPrefs@{ub}  V 1.2 (07.04.1999)  by Ralf Heinert  |
         @{fg shine}|@{fg text}____________________________________________________________|





         @{FG shine}@{b}Preferences@{ub}@{FG text} for @{b}RecoverDelDir@{ub}

         RecoverDelDirPrefs is a seperate program which is supposed to
         reside in Sys:prefs/ @{"?" rx "/ARexx/Check SYS:Prefs/RecoverDelDir.prefs 1.2"}
         Please click @{" here " rx " /Prefs/RecoverDelDir.prefs"} to run it.

         You can also run RecoverDelDir.prefs using the menu in the
         main program 'RecoverDelDir'.

         The prefsprogram will apperar automatically
         if you have just installed or updated RecoverDelDir.
         Then it creates prefs-files in ENV: and ENVARC:

         _____________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}


         @{b}GUI elements@{ub}:


         @{FG shine}@{b}Window height@{ub}@{FG text}

           Minimum amount of list entries to display.
           This determines the height of the main window.
           (min.3, max.31, default 8)


         @{b}@{FG shine}Window width@{FG text}@{ub}

           This in one of the factors affecting the windows
           width.
           If this valua is too high, the main window could
           perhaps not even appear.
           (min.20, max.86, default 56)


         @{FG shine}@{b}DelDir name@{ub}@{FG text}

           On SFS-formatted devices
           RecoverDelDir tries itself to figure out
           the name of the deldir.
           On failure it looks for the following names
           for the DELDIR directory:
              .DELDIR
              .Recycled
              .<user defined>
           If you renamed the DELDIR of your partition, you will
           have to enter the name as "user defined", so that
           RecoverDelDir can find the renamed DELDIR.

           Attention:
           The user defined name '.DELDIR' would be rejected,
           because this name is already internally used.
           But if your SFS-partition is casesensitive
           and its deldir-name is '.deldir' or 'DelDir'
           you can enter here the correct name.

           Note:
           The name of PFS(2)-partitions` deldir is always '.DELDIR'
           and on those '.DELDIR' is the only name, which is looked for.


         @{FG shine}@{b}SFSDelDirName@{ub}@{FG text} and @{FG shine}@{b}DeviceInfo@{ub}@{FG text}

           If you followed the installation guide, these programs will
           be copied to DOpus5:tools/RecoverDelDir/C/.

           But, however, if your RecoverDelDir is not residing in
           DOpus5:tools/ or if you insist of moving the two programs
           mentioned above somewhere else, you will have to tell
           RecoverDelDir.prefs the new location of these programs,
           as RecoverDelDir depends on both on them.


         @{FG shine}@{b}Temporary dir@{ub}@{FG text}

           If you are running out of RAM every time,
           you can enter a different path here for
           storing temporary files.
           You'd best choose a path on a FFS-device,
           but you *must not* choose a path on a
           partition using AFS, PFS2 or SFS.


         @{" Snapshot RDD " rx "/ARexx/SystemReq The button:*n*n- Snapshot RDD -"}

           This permanently saves the current dimension
           and position of the RecoverDelDir window.

           If you didn't start the prefs program
           from within RecoverDelDir,
           you`ll be told to run RecoverDelDir.

           ATTENTION:
           If you do not do this, and if you click on 'continue',
           the prefs-window seems to be frozen,
           but its is just waiting for you to start RecoverDelDir.
           Simply do it ;-)


           If you start the prefs program from within
           RecoverDelDir, please position the program`s
           window *before* choosing this function in
           order to permanently snapshot it.

           To unsnapshot the window, simply delete the
           file
           @{" ENVARC:Triton/ " rx "/ARexx/Lister ENVARC:Triton RecoverDelDir.win.1 SOURCE"} RecoverDelDir.win.1

           This directory is created in ENV: as well as
           in ENVARC: the very first time any triton
           program is quit.
           The particular file in question is created
           in ENV: when you quit RecoverDelDir for the
           very first time and will be copied to ENVARC:
           when you use the snapshot function.

           You can, by the way, snapshot any application
           using Triton.library (including RecoverDelDir)
           by using the @{" Triton " SYSTEM "SYS:Prefs/Triton"} prefs program.
           To do this, start the application and than
           start Triton-Prefs, where you should mark
           the program to be snapshot and then take a
           look at the "Windows" division.


         @{" Fonts " SYSTEM "SYS:Prefs/Font"}

           This gadget will run the Workbench`s
           font preferences program.

           '@{fg shine}@{b}Default Text setting ...@{ub}@{fg text}'
           determines the font used for the @{b}gadgets@{ub}
           and the @{b}string gadgets@{ub},
           thus taking influence on the @{b}width of the main window@{ub}

           '@{fg shine}@{b}System Text setting ...@{ub}@{fg text}
           determines the text used for the @{b}file list@{ub}.



         @{" Tritonprefs " SYSTEM "SYS:Prefs/Triton"}

           The Triton prefs program offers some further
           preferences options.
           I hope you have installed it in @{" SYS:Prefs/ " rx "/ARexx/Check SYS:Prefs/Triton"} ... ?


         _____________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}


           Oh, before I forget:
           RecoverDelDirPrefs also has to offer a @{fg shine}@{b}menu@{ub}@{fg text}:


         @{b}Help@{ub}

           switches the help text on/off.

           Note 1:
           Choosing this menu option will save
           all current preferences after checking
           their validity, including of course
           the status of this menu option.

           Note 2:
           If this menu option is enabled, a list
           of the used DelDir names will be displayed
           when you place the mouse pointer over
           the "user defined DelDir name" string gadget.

         @{b}Guide@{ub}

           displays this guide

         @{fg shine}@{b}--------------------------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

         @{b}Load previous@{ub}

           Loads the settings which have been set
           with "Use" or "Save" earlier.

         @{b}Load default@{ub}

           Loads the default settings

         @{b}Load again@{ub}

           Reloads the settings
           In case you hit the wrong keys :-)

         @{fg shine}@{b}--------------------------------------------@{ub}@{fg text}

         @{b}Save Use Cancel@{ub}

           Does exactly the same as the gadgets
           at the bottom of the prefs-window.

           Please note that before
           the program quits, the settings
           will be validated.
           Thus the delay ;-)
           If an error occurs,
           a requester will appear,
           the window will stay open
           and no settings will be saved.
           The settings also won't be saved
           if no settings have been changed.

         _____________________________________________________________@{fg shine}
         -------------------------------------------------------------@{fg text}



           Back to @{" RecoverDelDir.Guide " link "RecoverDelDir.Guide/Main"}





@endnode

